    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-02-09T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-02-09T04:00:00-05:00" n="273"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d273">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.516/807: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-02-09T16:00:00+07:00"
                            >February 9, 1944—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 10—12:21 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>269. Announced today that Kung succeeds Soong as Chairman of Bank of China Board,
                    Naval Attaché reports that Soong had told him that in this contingency he would
                    give up Foreign Office portfolio and <pb facs="0344" n="330" xml:id="pg_330"/>
                        CDS<note n="53" xml:id="d273fn53">China Defense Supplies.</note> and that
                    Wei Tao-ming was being considered for Foreign Office although no decision had
                    been made. Kung’s election said to be move to increase Government control of
                    banking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
